Or it's the part where your readers nod off or hit the "Back" button while cursing your name. Dr. Merlin is known to shout at her screen when she finds herself in the midst of too much information, even when it's not entertaining.

Exposition is not your ally.

My gentle readers already know the basic writing tip, "Show, don't tell," but Dr. Merlin still occasionally falls into long passages where nothing happens, or worse, too much happens. Exposition is the little devil on your shoulder urging you to get the history out of the way to reach the good parts (not to be confused with the devil on the other side encouraging the author to tell the audience every childhood detail of each character).

Exposition means telling the audience what happened, usually in simple prose. In film, exposition occurs when one character unloads a bunch of information onto another, akin to "The Rime of the Ancient Mariner." In fiction, it's the author doing the telling.

An example is necessary. As you read a story, you are informed that the heroine met her beloved at a certain place and time, they married in grand fashion, and her husband was murdered before her eyes. You wouldn't expect this entire sequence to take up two pages, with both he and she only getting two lines of dialogue each. You would expect the author to spend time developing the husband's character, showing through his speech and manner how deeply he loves his wife, and you would equally expect the heroine to reveal through various ways how his presence changed and enriched her life (especially if the story later tells you this outright). A proper introduction to the husband's character would allow you to become emotionally invested in his fate and give you insight into the heroine's character: what she saw in him, how deep their bond was, clues about her thoughts, beliefs, and dreams as reflected through his eyes, and so on. You would mourn his death with her, thus becoming more connected to the heroine herself.

In short, you would expect more substance on the simple storyline: "They met, they married, he died."

As a writer, you need to provide that substance. (*looks at metaphor, sighs, continues forward*) Sometimes it's tempting to rush past certain things. Perhaps you're introducing a new character and you know he used to be in the Air Force, he's now the night manager of a gas station, he was married twice, no kids, likes to go fishing on weekends, secretly dreams of owning the gas station someday, and had Eggs Benedict for breakfast.

I watched two newscasts from Columbus, Ohio. The first was a live broadcast from NBC 4 on the morning of August 13, 2011. The main story featured Shad Hostettler from Ashley, Ohio, who had stabbed his wife. His mugshot was shown, portraying him as quite menacing. The report was brief, about two minutes, as the situation was still unfolding. They mentioned he had stabbed her multiple times and had been arrested, which seemed like an appropriate amount of coverage.

The second story reported an early morning shooting of 18-year-old Travis Buyers in the Sharon Woods area. He was critically injured, with no arrests or suspects yet. The SWAT team was investigating. The coverage seemed short, possibly because he was Black or it happened in a Black neighborhood. I've noticed that crimes involving minorities often get less attention compared to when White victims are involved.

Another story was about a gunshot hole found in a Med-Flight helicopter. They speculated on where it happened and confirmed it was a .22 caliber bullet that hit the helicopter. Crime Stoppers offered a $5,000 reward for tips leading to an arrest.

The next report was about predicted rain and thunderstorms for Saturday afternoon, with temperatures expected to stay in the mid to low eighties over the weekend. The segment was short, possibly to entice viewers to keep watching.

Another report covered a robbery at a Clime Road UDF in Columbus, describing the suspect as a dark-skinned Black man wearing a hoodie. He was about six feet tall and weighed around 150 pounds. The emphasis on his race and skin tone seemed excessive.

Lastly, there was a story about Rene Rodriguez, a convicted Texas drug kingpin, sentenced for conspiring to distribute large amounts of marijuana to Ohio. Interestingly, they described his sentence as "300 months" instead of 25 years, perhaps to make it sound harsher. They also noted he was Hispanic, which seemed unnecessary to the report.

An ETF, or exchange-traded fund, is a security designed to track an index, commodity, or a basket of assets, similar to an index fund but more flexible and traded like a stock on an exchange. ETFs offer the diversification of an index fund and the advantages of single stock ownership, such as the ability to short sell, buy on margin, and purchase as little as one share in any transaction. While these benefits are highly appealing, the expense ratios of ETFs are much lower than those of average mutual funds. However, there are some downsides, such as the need to pay commissions on any trade involving ETFs, similar to a stock order. Another advantage of ETFs is the wide variety of funds available. Although these benefits are clearly stated, it is always wise for a savvy financial investor to assess whether the stated benefits, such as diversification, truly exist and to what extent. To explore this, we will examine the ETF IHF and compare it to the top 10 holdings comprising the ETF to determine whether the advantages of owning a single ETF are akin to those of holding a diversified portfolio of ten stocks and whether there are better configurations of the same stocks for a more optimal Sharpe ratio or return.

To evaluate the ETF, including every holding would be cumbersome, so we have decided to only include the top ten holdings, accounting for 63.58% of all assets in the ETF. Below are the top 10 holdings and their percentage of total assets.

To estimate how well these ten stocks represent the ETF IHF as a whole, we can use the current % of assets, normalized to 100%, to calculate each stock's contribution to a portfolio's Beta and Return if the portfolio were entirely made up of these 10 stocks in the proportion that the ETF has established through their holdings. The calculations of Beta and return are included in the chart below.

From the chart above, it is evident that a portfolio containing only the top 10 holdings has a return 6.11% higher than the ETF, a 16% increase in returns. It is also evident that the Beta of the top ten holdings is 0.12 lower than the ETF as a whole. Based on the results thus far, it seems that a portfolio of just the top 10 holdings could provide a higher return with a lower Beta. However, there is a possibility that the means of these two portfolios may not be statistically different from each other.

To assess whether these portfolios are statistically different, the standard deviation of each of the top 10 stocks is determined and normalized to 100% to compare their accumulated standard deviation to that of the ETF IHF.

Referring to Figure 17, there was a sharp decline in commuter log submissions in the project's third month, which was somewhat discouraging. It's difficult to pinpoint the exact cause. With winter arriving at a New England campus, there is a noticeable reduction in people commuting by bicycle or on foot, which could partly explain the decline. December also marks the end of the fall semester, a busy time for everyone completing schoolwork and processing grades, so filling out the commuter log might have been overlooked by many. Additionally, December kicks off the busy holiday season with a month-long break for students and faculty, during which many don't need to come to campus. Classes resume in late January for the spring semester, which might explain the low number of logs for that month. However, this doesn't explain the low submissions in February. It's possible that projects like this have an initial burst of energy and excitement that naturally wanes. To counter this trend, we launched Carpool Challenge Week in March, a special campaign to reinvigorate the initiative, which successfully increased log submissions for that month. Thus, one of the challenges we faced was maintaining project momentum in light of natural decreases in engagement and the specific challenges of holiday and semester breaks in higher education.

Another challenge for this project (or any alternative commuting project) is the fact that people enjoy the freedom, independence, and flexibility of driving their cars, deeply ingrained in our culture. Therefore, providing incentives for alternative commuting modes is essential. We offered many prizes in the form of gift certificates to local restaurants, coffee shops, massage therapists, the local independent bookstore, and even some larger national chain stores. It would have been interesting to see how larger prizes might have influenced participation, such as giving away a nice bicycle, hybrid car, or electric car. This might have also helped address the dip in engagement the project experienced. The nature of the prizes didn't really change during the project. However, if the prize values increased over the project's course, it might have helped. The gift cards seemed adequate at the project's start, but if we had announced a couple of bicycles in December and then a hybrid or electric car in January, participation and engagement might have increased rather than decreased.

While exploring the Library of Congress's collection of early Edison films, I decided to watch all the trick films, totaling fifteen from 1895 to 1901. These films typically use creative editing to create illusions. My film study mainly focused on describing the aesthetics of most trick films and examining the evolutionary traits present in some of the later films. Generally, the trick films at the turn of the century are set-bound, composed within a frontal proscenium, feature no camera movement, use long and medium shots, and adhere to the strict one shot = one film methodology. However, some films in the early 20th century dared to break these guidelines by introducing elements like multiple shots.

One of the most prominent features shared by trick films is that they are shot on an indoor set within the frame of a frontal proscenium. The camera does not move from its proscenium position to follow people or objects. This composition was very common in early films, with roots in theatre, and specifically for trick films, in vaudeville and magic acts. One limitation inherent in using the stage is that characters in trick films usually move only side-to-side and do not walk toward or away from the camera. For instance, in the film "Uncle Josh in a Spooky Hotel" (1900), actors enter from the right and move back and forth along the horizontal axis. Even when they leave the frame, the camera does not follow them.

The frontal proscenium style of composition also means that shots are typically long shots, and more rarely, medium shots. No trick film in the Edison catalog uses close-up shots. This borrows from the theatre and vaudeville tradition, where the audience would see the entire performance at once, framed by the stage's borders. As with most early films, actors do not move from the mid-ground towards the camera, so close-ups never occur.

Generally, most early trick films follow the pattern that one conceptual shot equals a film. This limits the length of most trick films to about a minute or less, depending on the frames per second used. It also limits the dramatic or narrative usage of trick films; most focus on short vaudeville-style tricks, such as magic, disappearing, and switching acts with little story. However, note that in a trick film, one conceptual shot in the viewer's eyes does not actually equal one physical shot. A single "shot" may actually consist of several joined together to produce the illusion of appearance or disappearance. Look closely at "The Execution of Mary, Queen of Scots" (1895), one of the earlier trick films. A more thorough inspection reveals the moment where the physical shot with Mary's severed "head" begins, even though the whole film conceptually seems like one shot to the viewer.

The traditional "Gothic Novel" is described as an "oxymoron for 'Old-New'" by Ian Watt in The Rise of the Gothic Novel. This genre has faced both criticism and praise, accused of lacking depth yet celebrated for its 'terrible sublime' quality. Horace Walpole's The Castle of Otranto, the first "Gothic Novel," fused "ancient and modern" romance elements to craft the proto-Gothic genre and a new literary expression. Walpole used "old" theatrical elements and 'new' nature mimicry in 'modern' novels to create what he termed "A Gothic Story." The Gothic genre draws from medieval gothic theatre, architecture, and traditions. Even at the time of its publication, "gothic" described various peoples, styles, and eras, and was seen as archaic compared to "modern" advancements. The blend of theatrical "Gothic" with the novel's format provides an intimate view of characters' psychology, allowing Gothic works to endure, appearing both obsolete and new to later readers.

A key Gothic theme is Chivalry. The medieval concept of training a knight is both preserved and altered in The Castle of Otranto. Chivalry was vital to Gothic writers for its representation of the classic, brave, honorable knight—a standard they found lacking in their society. By using chivalric ideals, the "gothic past" is romanticized, hinting at Gothic's evolution to Romantic, aiming to better the present. Walpole wrote during political unrest, worried about the future. Engaged in politics and facing accusations, he might have believed that the era's morality and "goodness" were lost in contemporary society, a theme seen in characters like Frederic. Frederic, described with many chivalric traits, is a prince who has suffered tragedy and is thought to have been killed by infidels. The "gallant and courteous Knight" image is exaggerated, introducing Gothic excess.

Supply chain management involves the processes of moving goods from the customer order through raw materials, supply, production, and distribution to the customer. The term was coined by consultant Keith Oliver in 1982. He described the comprehensive process of planning, implementing, and controlling activities within the supply chain to efficiently meet customer needs. There are six key elements in a supply chain: production, supply, inventory, location, transportation, and information. Business managers use these elements to deliver optimal customer service.

Production is the first step in the supply chain. It serves as the foundation for the entire process, outlining when, why, where, and how everything will be produced. Managers need to understand customer desires, often looking to the market as the primary indicator of demand. After analyzing the market, managers determine what products to produce and in what quantities. Once they decide these, they select the optimal location and plant for production, considering customer demand and satisfaction. Once the production location is set, managers focus on scheduling workloads and maintaining equipment. Every detail is crucial, as poor planning can result in significant time and financial losses. For example, when I worked at Wal-Mart and Target, both companies had designed processes for every business aspect, ensuring smooth operations without confusion.

The second key element is supply. Supply involves strategic decisions to define a facility's core capabilities, from which outsourcing partnerships may develop. A company might have several production divisions for a single product, each with its own equipment, workers, and specialties. Managers must select the best division for various product processes and may choose to outsource work to other companies. The primary reason for outsourcing is to create speed, providing quality and flexibility while reducing or maintaining low costs.

Victorian novels are known for their meticulous attention to detail and their focus on the aristocracy of the era. However, "Oliver Twist" and "Wuthering Heights" are two novels considered Victorian that deviate from this tradition. Both novels incorporate elements of mystery and the bizarre, which are uncommon in the literature of that period, thereby enhancing the characterization within each work and offering deep insights into the characters' motives and emotions.

"And now, a multitude of bewildering and confusing ideas crowded his mind. He seemed to be still walking between Sikes and Crackit, who were angrily disputing, for their voices echoed in his ears; and when he caught his own attention, he found that he was speaking to them. Suddenly, he was startled by the report of firearms; loud cries and shouts rose into the air; lights flashed before his eyes, and everything was noise and turmoil, as if an unseen hand hurriedly carried him away. Through these rapid visions, there was an undefined, uneasy consciousness of pain that continuously wearied and tormented him."

The two novels frequently utilize this mystery through dream sequences or dreamlike states, although the content and function vary in each specific case. In "Oliver Twist," these strange events often reveal insights into Oliver's inner layers, what troubles him, and his awareness of the true nature of the happenings around him. When the shooting of Oliver is revisited in chapter 28, Oliver vividly relives the event as if in a dream while struggling to find help. This passage underscores Oliver's lack of control over the unfolding events and the dire state of his health, strongly embodied through his hallucinations of Sikes and Crackit. The shooting itself overwhelms him, all his senses are numbed as he fails to notice the "unseen hand" that carries him away; he experiences his despair again, detached from the shock of pain, as the pain is now constant and linked with fear rather than surprise. With Oliver being overwhelmed, the question arises about whose will caused his misfortune, for it was certainly not his own. This incident reinforces the notion that Oliver has little control over anything, even unable to attempt to influence the outcome of events, even when his life is in danger. This selection also implies a growing sense of defeat in Oliver, as if old Fagin had begun to break him, forcing him to accept this despair, affecting his ability to react. Otherwise, it could be assumed that Oliver would have made some effort, at least for his own life's sake.

"The day passed – day! There was no day; it disappeared as soon as it came – and night came again; night so long, yet so short; long in its dreadful silence and short in its fleeting hours."

A few years ago, I worked in an after-school program tutoring elementary students. I tried my best to assist them in subjects they struggled with, though my strengths were in English and reading. One of the instructors asked me to help a young boy named Adrian (I believe he was in third or fourth grade) who had significant reading difficulties. I realized something was wrong; he had very unusual issues. Some letters he could pronounce perfectly, while others he couldn't at all, which was quite strange. Although he was of Latino descent, he spoke perfect English. We were at an impasse until I met his mother. I was supervising a few students while the rest were on a field trip when she arrived. His mother didn't speak any English, only Spanish. With my very limited Spanish skills (as I was just learning), we managed to communicate. That's when it struck me: Adrian could read, but he didn't know the English alphabet well. I'm not sure if this realization helped him much, but I hope he's doing better now.

I share this story to highlight the language barrier issue in schools, especially in California. It shows that the problem isn't always as obvious as it seems. Even for a child who speaks perfect English, reading can be a significant challenge. I think we can all agree this problem exists, so what can we do? In Adrian's case, the solution was straightforward: English reading tutoring, focusing on the alphabet and pronunciations. But for many children who barely speak English, the solution is much more complex. There isn't one single answer. The dual language system, mainstream immersion, private tutors, ESL classes—none of these alone will solve the problem. The key is in combining all these methods!

First, the dual language system is a great idea. It's beneficial not only for children whose first language is Spanish but for all children. "Children in two-way bilingual education programs have been found to outperform their peers academically." There is much fear surrounding this idea, that it's a waste of resources and that most children in schools won't benefit. But that's false. If we implemented these programs as the norm in classrooms, rather than the exception, all children would benefit. How do we go about this? Do we require all teachers to be bilingual? No, that would be unreasonable and somewhat unrealistic. However, I do believe there's no reason we can't have bilingual aides, tutors, or whatever you want to call them.

From a young age, most of us are told there is something greater than us, beyond our comprehension. Some are sent to Sunday school to learn about it, while others seek answers in temples or within themselves. Many of us readily embrace the religions passed down by our parents. However, some completely reject them, denying that anything exists beyond our egocentric universe. We might adopt one set of values only to later change our minds. Whatever path we choose, we strive to define a part of ourselves through our unique spiritual perspectives. We seek a light in the darkness to guide us out of the shadows and into the sunshine.

"A cardinal," my father replied when I asked about his favorite bird. We sat on the front porch, listening to the rain on the tin roof above and smoking cigarettes together. The rain flowed from the gutters, drowning the plants along the porch's edge. He gazed into the rain, his look a mix of searching and reminiscing. Over the past few months, he had grown thinner, his clothes hanging loosely, his hair sparser than I remembered. He continued to gaze into the rain, avoiding eye contact. I felt alone, afraid, unable to talk to my father about how much I would miss him, as discussing it would make it more real for both of us. I hugged him, sat down again, moved my chair closer, and joined him in watching the June twilight rain.

My father passed away in December that year, five days after my twenty-second birthday. The chemo and radiation didn't ease his suffering, only extended his life a few months beyond the doctors' projections; I couldn't find value in prolonged suffering. What kind of God would allow this, I wondered. Alone at night, I offered no prayers. If God existed, I thought, he had stopped listening to me long ago.

I didn't want to watch him transition from this life to the next. So I didn't. I couldn’t watch the life that created me come to an end. I wanted to remember him for how he lived, not how he died. Besides, I knew him better than they did, better than his family did; Dad wouldn't want his only child to witness his passing. I curled up in my bed for three days, waiting for the news.

No one even called me.

John Taylor of Caroline was an early and enthusiastic supporter of Republicanism. Although primarily an agriculturist, his profession and brief political career made him known for his dedication and outspoken nature on matters of personal freedom and government. His commitment to an agrarian system formed the foundation of almost all his views on government. He aimed to preserve and promote what he regarded as the most superior profession, which influenced his arguments on sovereignty, constitutionality, and even the judicial system.

John Taylor believed the United States had a great opportunity to create an ideal system because there was no native tradition to hinder the creators of the government, allowing for the establishment of self-governance. He firmly believed in the natural rights of individuals and their interdependence—meaning that if one right is denied, all rights would fail, diminishing the value of those remaining. Therefore, these rights should be beyond the reach of the government. He asserted that what some called the "state of nature" meant that those with physical strength and malevolent intelligence benefited, but in civilization, this should not be the case.

To create this ideal society, Taylor believed a government must be established that accounts for the inherent good and evil within humanity. Taylor held very firm views on dualistic morality. He claimed, "As government is exercised by man, all its virtues and vices must be human" (Ibid., pg. 167). He defined good principles as those that protect private property, improve agriculture, and discourage capitalism, believing that a government founded on good principles would function fairly regardless of its administration, which would inevitably be led by greed and self-interest. He viewed self-interest as the motivation behind all human actions, but this trait was only considered evil when it led beyond the creation of a society based on the public good to sub-societies living at the expense of others. A good government was necessary to restrain man's natural evil, and even then, it must be carefully monitored to prevent the addition of bad principles.

Like many staunch Republicans of his time, Taylor called for a strict interpretation of the Constitution. He desired an extremely limited Federal government, with no more rights or powers than explicitly stated in the Constitution. He recognized that an extensive Federal government was costly and likely despotic. However, he believed that a simple, literal interpretation was dangerous, and without reference to the writers' intent, such a method could easily become corrupt. He also considered the Declaration of Independence to be the true charter of the United States because it more explicitly described the country as a group of sovereign states rather than a single nation.

As I looked down, my mind was blank while trying to comprehend the view in front of me. I examined it dispassionately and silently, with a practiced awareness that analyzed without connecting to any abstract understanding. Thoughts came and went quickly, so smoothly that it felt like I had no real thoughts, only an active and flowing experience of what I saw.

Once, following advice from an artist I worked with, I bought an art instruction book called "The New Drawing on the Right Side of the Brain." I had wanted to learn to draw since I was six, and this book covered everything from understanding what a pencil is to how the brain interprets lines. One technique it taught was to put a square frame around any picture the artist wanted to study, transforming an overwhelming image, like a bowl of fruit on a kitchen table connected to a dining room, into a simple, manageable picture.

At that moment, looking at the bowl in front of me, I couldn't mentally project that artist's frame. I was overwhelmed, filled with awe, and could only stand there in wonder. Picasso had his blue period, Monet loved greenery, and Italian Renaissance masters displayed a spectrum of colors. If I had any pretensions of casting my view as worthy of the title "Artistic," then before me was the beginning of my picture, the start of my story, "Work in Brown."

My fingertips touched my chosen artistic tool, as muscles tightened and relaxed while my hand moved through space, my mind's will taking shape in what could be my most creative moment. Water swirled, serene and smooth, crystal clear and clean. Flakes broke away and disappeared. Muscles tightened again, moving more quickly and anxiously, my hand hit the toilet handle again. The offensive brown package refused to move, stubbornly sticking to the bottom of the toilet.

Holding the mop loosely, feet a foot apart, a green tie uncomfortably knotted around my neck, I frowned slightly at the rude bundle of processed animal and plant matter left as a message for those who cleaned the Rite Aid bathrooms. A few more flushes, a few more peaceful introspective moments, then my hand moved towards the wall, grabbed the end of the toilet paper, and began wrapping itself like an oven mitt. Standing upright, then bending at the waist, my hand slowly dipped into the bowl, like a mother reaching into the oven for the Thanksgiving turkey...

Teenagers are facing fatal accidents while driving. Various factors combine to create this deadly trend among America's youngest drivers. The National Institutes of Health explains that part of the issue is that teenagers' brains are not yet equipped to handle the dangers of driving. A lack of experience is also at the core of the problem, leading not only to more fatal accidents but also to higher rates of vehicle rollovers, speeding, and driving off the road.  

Teenagers fare worse when traveling with peers, which anyone with common sense knows they do regularly. A study by the Southern California Injury Prevention Research Center showed a correlation between the age of passengers and the occurrence of traffic accidents.  

California and other states have tried to improve teen driving safety by requiring temporary provisional licenses that restrict driving hours and prohibit other minors as passengers.  

However, in my view, provisional licenses are merely stopgap measures. The real issue is that, as a group, the youngest drivers are statistically unable to adequately manage the risks and responsibilities. Psychologist Marvin Zuckerman believes even 18 is too young for a regular driver's license. USA Today reports Zuckerman's research suggests a common desire among those under 19-20 to take risks for thrills. It makes sense then to delay driving until this thrill-seeking tendency begins to stabilize. If we continue issuing licenses to young teens, we'll continue to see fatal accidents, and the death toll could reach staggering levels in the coming years. By 2010, the children of the Baby Boomers will be eligible to drive, and millions of new teenage drivers will be ready to take to the roads.  

Legislation addressing this issue would be relatively straightforward. Schools could continue to provide driver's education to start the learning process for future drivers, but no one under 18 could drive a motor vehicle. A provisional permit could still be issued before granting a full license, with a required number of practical driving hours. The specific number of hours could be based on those already required by most states, such as California's current requirement of 6 hours of in-car training and 50 hours of practice with an adult. Since deadly statistics for teen drivers come from a cross-section of all states, uniform national legislation would be a reasonable and effective means of protecting teens nationwide.  

The legislation I propose is by no means a novel idea.

This paper explores three aspects of Central Auditory Processing Disorder (CAPD). It begins with a brief definition of the disorder, followed by an explanation of the diagnosis process, including common characteristics or "red flags." Finally, the paper discusses how a teacher in a mainstream classroom environment can support a student with CAPD.

Central Auditory Processing Disorder (CAPD), also known as Auditory Processing Disorder (APD), "refers to the efficiency and effectiveness with which the central nervous system (CNS) processes auditory information. In a narrow sense, (C)AP refers to the perceptual processing of auditory information within the CNS and the neurobiological activities that underlie this processing, resulting in electrophysiological auditory potentials" (American Speech-Language-Hearing Association, 2005). This means it is a disorder where the central nervous system (i.e., the brain) cannot correctly process what is heard. Individuals with CAPD can hear normally, so they are not considered "hearing impaired"; rather, the part of the brain responsible for translating what we hear, distinguishing words, or differentiating conversation from background noise, does not function as it should.

The first mention of what would become CAPD dates back to the mid-1950s, when it was called "auditory imperception" (American Speech-Language-Hearing Association, 2005) during evaluations of children with communicative disorders. The Italian research team of Bocca, Calearo, and Cassinari began developing tests for these children in 1954. In 1961, Kimura "introduced dichotic testing and formulated a model to explain the physiology of the CANS underlying dichotic perception" (American Speech-Language-Hearing Association, 2005). A national conference in 1977 spurred further research on children with CAPD.

CAPD can manifest in various ways: individuals may be unable to localize or hear sound in space, may struggle to differentiate between two or more "acoustic events" (sound occurrences), may fail to recognize sound patterns, and may not detect changes in speech (such as discerning sarcasm through tone changes). One sound may be masked by a subsequent sound, they may lack the ability to synthesize sound clues (interpreting them meaningfully to act upon), and they may be unable to determine the sequence in which auditory information is presented (Ferre).

To diagnose CAPD, patients undergo "systematic observation of listening behavior and/or performance on auditory function tests," conducted by "audiologists, SLPs, psychologists, and others using a variety of measures to evaluate auditory-related skills" (American Speech-Language-Hearing Association, 2005). This may involve questionnaires, surveys, and observation of auditory behaviors, such as how the patient responds to certain stimuli. Currently, there is no single tool or test used consistently to achieve a high diagnostic success rate, and no known cause of the disorder. Many tests present the patient with multiple, simultaneous auditory stimuli, asking them to differentiate specific items like a series of words or numbers. More advanced tests include recording acoustic signals within the ear and measuring responses to these signals.

In my pursuit of education in social work, I aim to follow a career path with the Division of Family and Children Services to assist children who have been abused or neglected and to support families in distress. The values I bring to the field of social work include service, respect, ethics, a commitment to improving relationships among others, and enhancing my professional skills to remain competent. These core values are crucial not only to social workers but also personally important to me.

I have always wanted to help others but was uncertain about the career path I wanted to take. Throughout high school and college, I witnessed many individuals deny their problems, and some used less than ideal coping mechanisms. Due to these observations, I chose to pursue a Bachelor's degree in Psychology. Still unsure of my career direction, I decided to take a break after graduating from Piedmont College in 2009. One summer day, I visited a friend who introduced me to a nervous sixteen-year-old boy on her couch. She explained that he was there to escape his abusive parents. The next day, I learned he had called the police to his parents' home. To see if I could help, I drove over to his parents' house. There, I privately expressed my concerns to the police and informed them of my recent graduation in Psychology from Piedmont College. The police asked me to talk to the parents since the law had no solution for the teenager. When I questioned the parents, they seemed nervous and used excuses to describe their son's "manipulative" behavior in involving outsiders to settle "simple" disputes. After this experience, I began to seriously consider a career in social work to assist children with family disputes.

Another critical value for social work is social justice. As a society, we claim the importance of the individual and mourn those we have lost. However, the concept of the "individual" society holds often follows outdated traditions rather than true uniqueness. Thus, if society mourns lost individuals, why do we strive to be like "everyone else?" I am an individual and dislike limiting myself to be like others. Throughout high school and college, I protested against social injustice whenever possible: dyeing my hair unnatural colors, wearing clothes that match my personality, having my ears pierced beyond the traditional set, declaring my involvement with GSBA (Gay Straight Bisexual Alliance), and opposing racism and discrimination whenever I witnessed them. I believe in social justice and will continue to protest against social injustice.

This paper discusses the Biological and Sociocultural models concerning insomnia. The Biological model focuses on genetic information and medical aspects of health. The Sociocultural model examines environmental relationships and their applications to race, ethnicity, demographics, and socioeconomic status. The review of insomnia analyzes these models and explains each research piece chosen to clarify and illustrate the models. The explanations and findings from the research are then critically examined to highlight their specific strengths and weaknesses.

Sleep disorders can be classified as primary sleep disorders, those related to another mental disorder, or those related to other issues. Primary sleep disorders include Dyssomnias or Parasomnias, while those related to other mental disorders are associated with Axis I or Axis II disorders. Other categories of sleep disorders might result from medical complications or substance intake. Dyssomnias include Primary Insomnia, Primary Hypersomnia, Narcolepsy, Breathing-Related Sleep Disorder, Circadian Rhythm Sleep Disorder, and Dyssomnia Not Otherwise Specified (NOS). Primary Insomnia involves difficulties in achieving or maintaining adequate sleep, while Primary Hypersomnia involves difficulties staying awake for at least a month. Narcolepsy involves cataplexy and/or automatic REM. While Dyssomnias focus on initiating and maintaining sleep, Parasomnias are associated with behavioral abnormalities and/or physiological occurrences. Parasomnias include Nightmare Disorder, Sleep Terror Disorder, Sleepwalking Disorder, and Parasomnias Not Otherwise Specified. Sleep disorders related to another mental disorder involve sleep difficulties due to Axis I (Clinical Disorders) or Axis II (Personality Disorders or Mental Retardation). This review focuses on insomnia and generally on primary sleep disorders concerning the biological and sociocultural models.

The biological model of sleep disorders focuses on genes, heritable factors, and physiologically acquired aspects of sleep disorders. Neurons in the hypothalamus containing orexin are responsible for regulating sleep and wakefulness. This study experimented with mice and found that there are specific GABAB receptors on the orexin neurons responsible for sleep/wake states. Activation of the GABAA receptor induces responses that promote sleep. Inhibiting its firing can reduce anxiety and induce sleep. The GABAB agonist (baclofen) increased sleep time (Matsuki et al., 2009). These results suggest that mouse models can be generalized to human studies. This indicates a genetic and environmental basis for the physical GABAB receptor in humans. A problem or absence of this receptor could alter one's ability to achieve adequate sleep without medication. The sociocultural implication of this study is that if the phenotype was inherited, it could regulate sleep, and an alteration of the receptor would naturally disturb sleep for an individual, negatively impacting life aspects such as school, career, and daily events involving monotonous tasks and focus.

I have been a student at University Park for about two and a half years, or four and a half semesters. For many people, including myself, getting around campus can be challenging. During my freshman year, I stayed in the East Halls dormitory, which is essentially the easternmost part of campus, excluding the stadium and Bryce Jordan Center. Walking from my home in Stuart Hall to classes in faraway places like the Willard Building, near the center of campus, could take up to 25 minutes on foot, especially when the weather was bad, as it often is in State College. In a conversation with an alum not much older than me, I found out that not long ago, the East Halls dorms were separated from the rest of the school by large areas of unused land. Today, that empty space has been filled with sports fields, huge new buildings including a new Creamery and a new health services building, and is surrounded by apartments. As our campus continues to grow, moving from one place to another is becoming increasingly difficult. What is the best solution to the mobility problem? On a college campus, it is the bicycle. But just having a bike won't solve any problems. Students need to ride them, and the campus needs to be designed to accommodate cyclists' needs. I was talking to a friend who recently resumed cycling after a break of several years. He mentioned he couldn't understand why he ever stopped. "Bikes are great," he said, "for a while, it wasn't cool to ride a bike, but now it's the only way to get around." Besides being good for your health, cycling is the most efficient way to travel. A bowl of oatmeal and some physical effort can take you 30 miles or more. Like many undergraduates, I now live off-campus, just as far from the center of campus as some dorms. The smartest decision I've made this year was to buy a bike. Every day, I have classes in the Thomas Building, which is easily a twenty-five-minute walk from my home. Riding a bike can reduce that time to 5 minutes if I pedal fast enough. The only problem is, Pollock Road is the most direct route to the Thomas Building from my house, and it's not always easy to travel on, whether on a bike or not. There are benefits to walking too, but personally, I'm too busy to walk. Without my bike, walking would be my only reliable option to get to class. Walking to Thomas every day would take an extra 30 to 40 minutes out of my day. That's over two and a half hours every week. Add to that all the other time I would need to spend walking to and from other classes, appointments, etc. That's more time than I can afford to lose.

Aldous Huxley critiques the looming threat posed by both technology and the capitalist system that reinforces it through the creation of a dystopia in the novel "Brave New World." The people in the novel prioritize community over the individual and are conditioned from the start to seek immediate pleasure above all else. The citizens are revealed to be pawns in a larger scheme, confined to a single ideology dictated by the World Controller. Viewing the work through a Marxist lens, one can notice the author's underlying skepticism regarding the development of these systems. Frequent Marxist terms like homogenization and reification underscore Huxley's commentary on the flaws of the emerging economy of his time.

Capitalism is satirized through the Marxist concept known as false consciousness. Essentially, the common citizens are prevented from understanding their true economic relations with other classes, as they are primarily focused on their own gain. This is seen as a result of ideological control over the proletariat and common workers, something evident in the conditioning of people in "Brave New World." The common classes, such as Delta and Gamma, have no real will of their own; through hypnopaedia, the urge to consume, spend, and indulge is greatly enhanced. As previously mentioned, this is manipulated by the World Controller. Hegemony, the idea that social class groups are entirely dominated by a separate group of individuals, is clearly at play here. The lower classes are completely unaware of the manipulation, literally 'buying into an ideology that supports that structure' (i.e., capitalism and consumerism). The upper classes are born with the capacity to be aware of it but do nothing; few Alphas or Betas, aside from characters like Bernard, do much more than accept their place. In fact, the interactions among social classes, as will be discussed further, significantly indicate the perceived oppression of capitalism.

In "Brave New World," relationships between disparate individuals do not exist. The novel seems to refuse to differentiate the characters—they lack depth even among the main characters. Perhaps Huxley is suggesting that the rise of technology and capitalism together deprives humanity of free will and expression. Love does not exist, nor do the extremes of any single emotion; rather, interactions remain superficial, portrayed distinctly through male comments about women's physical appearance (e.g., pneumatic quality) and women's unashamed remarks about their experiences. Furthermore, each societal class's satisfaction with its status in the hierarchy indicates the socioeconomic effects of capitalism. Their absolute obedience to their role in the community aligns with Marxist thought on the proletariat, who are falsely assured of their own superiority as long as they continue to consume, obey, and conform with their peers.

Almost four years ago, I took a course on Islam at CBC. One of the main topics of intense discussion was whether Islam is a hostile religion. I believe this question is even more relevant today. Looking back at events since 9/11, I have observed the mass media's shift from a hostile view of Islam and extremists to a significant tolerance for Islam in America. I doubt that in 2001 we could have imagined a presidential candidate named Barack Obama, with evident Muslim heritage in his family.

The biography of the Prophet interests me because, according to what I know of Muhammad's history, it contradicts his personality. In the past, I believed that Muhammad forced conversions to Islam. He would conquer tribes and compel them to adopt Islam. However, the biography portrays Muhammad as a sort of martyr, misunderstood and humble towards others. Over time, people recognized the 'truth' in his teachings and sought him out.

There are also striking similarities between the ministries of Jesus and the 'miracles' of Muhammad. Notably, he multiplied mutton and milk to feed more than forty men. This writing style suggests to me that the authors intended to depict Muhammad as a humble prophet who lived truthfully and performed miracles without proving anything. This narrative is troubling because it diminishes the miracles and life of Jesus Christ. To me, it seems they are trying to appropriate the life and essence of Jesus through Muhammad.

Furthermore, many stories in the biography seem to aim at proving 'witness' or how people 'independently' converted to Islam. The problem is that many stories come from a third-party perspective. In these stories, the author describes hearing from someone who heard from someone else, and so on. I found this approach unsatisfactory because, while intended to provide proof of the stories' truths, it made them seem more dubious.

What bothers me most is the attempt to elevate Muhammad as a godly man who was humble, endearing, wise, and gentle. However, historical accounts contradict the idea of Muhammad as gentle and humble, and I wonder if Muslims today know the true history behind Muhammad's rise to power.

During Jesus' lifetime, his teachings and beliefs were quickly overshadowed by the development of Christian thought after his death. Looking at this history broadly, we see Christianity increasingly straying from its origins. Today's world seems to show a growing awareness and unprecedented progressiveness. While traditionalists remain and resist any thought beyond what they were taught, this group may not be influential enough to affect the whole. Among Christians, historical awareness will greatly increase in future years. There will be a desire to distinguish the doctrines added to Christianity over time from the true intentions of its founder. Although it may take decades or even centuries, the outcome will be inevitable: a major reversal in the trend of Christian history. There will be a process of returning to its original form. A movement will grow that removes layers of doctrine as if time were moving backward, leaving only the concepts Jesus introduced to humanity on behalf of God before any other thinkers made such claims. As this trend sweeps through the United States and Europe, influencing masses to worship as if living in Jesus' time, following only his ideas, the church as an institution will remain strong to lead the way. However, because the theological clock will have moved backward, the extreme diversity in Christendom will reverse into more uniformity of belief and practice. Between regions, denominations, and divisions of all kinds, instead of differences, we will see increasing similarities. Human history is filled with great reversions. Just one example is how Christians were once persecuted, shunned, and killed by the Roman Empire, but later that empire became a Christian institution. Our country has transitioned from African-American slavery to African-American leadership. The great reversion coming in our future will play out in the realm of Christianity, undoing history in search of the source and reducing diversity in the process. It is crucial to note that part of what will make this process possible is interpreting Jesus' words metaphorically, rather than as literal statements. So, what has happened since Jesus' time?

If we look far enough back into history, we find only Judaism, which provided the theological starting point for Christianity. By the time the Romans took control of Jerusalem in 63 B.C.E., monotheism, the perception of a divinely revealed religion, and the authority of the Hebrew scriptures were all central to the religion. The Jewish population did not share a single spirit. They were divided into Sadducees, Pharisees, Essenes, Zealots, and a majority of common people.

I believe that The Jungle illustrates how humans are inherently greedy and self-centered deep down. They focus solely on their own benefit and strive to improve their lives as much as possible, never caring for those beneath them. This theme is shown in various ways in The Jungle, particularly through the factory owners and managers who are determined to expand their companies regardless of the consequences. They disregard anyone who stands in their way or any harm caused by their progress. As Upton Sinclair describes, "The line of buildings stood clear against the sky; here and there rose the great chimneys, with smoke streaming away to the world's end." Sinclair tries to depict the immense damage caused by pollution, highlighting the indifference of factory owners towards any person or animal that might suffer. They ignore the plumes of smoke from factories or the runoff of animal waste surrounding Packingtown.

The owners and managers also show no concern for their workers who labor to make them wealthy. They will do anything to save or earn an extra dollar, creating an environment filled with jealousy and hatred, devoid of loyalty or decency, where a man's worth is nothing compared to a dollar. They force workers into long hours and can suddenly lay off large numbers of them without notice, compensation, or assistance in finding new jobs. During the era depicted in The Jungle, few laws or regulations protected workers' safety or welfare, allowing managers and owners to exploit their workers, pushing them to work faster and in terrible conditions. Although not explicitly stated in the book, those who lived and worked themselves to death in Packingtown were expected to endure these harsh conditions. There were no agencies or organizations to support the workers, and while unions existed, they often exploited the workers further, profiting from their struggles. The workers were treated so poorly and trapped in the system of Packingtown that they were described as slaves, "A population, low-class and mostly foreign, hanging on the brink of starvation, dependent on the whims of men as brutal and unscrupulous as old-time slave drivers; under such circumstances, immorality is as inevitable and prevalent as under the system of chattel slavery."

Edgar Allan Poe considered "Dream-land" to be one of his better poems. In the poem, Poe uses the term "Thulé" in lines 6 and 56, which Mabbott traces back to Virgil. Virgil used this term to describe an island north of Britain, regarded by the Greeks as the edge of the known world. Although Virgil did use the term, there is a more contemporary source worth noting, as Poe was very interested in German authors. This quote is significant because it shows Poe's familiarity with Goethe's works. Karl J. Arndt, in his book "Poe’s Politian and Goethe’s Mignon," discusses the similarity between their poems and concludes that Poe was imitating Goethe.

The Oxford Companion to English Literature notes that Goethe was a celebrated writer of the poetic drama "Faust," published in two parts, the first in 1808 and the second in 1832, the year of Goethe's death. In the second part of "Faust," there is a short poem titled "The King of Thulé," about a king whose wife dies after giving him a goblet. After her death, the king drinks heavily and weeps from the memory of his dead queen. He decides it is time for him to die, leaving his possessions to his children, except for the goblet. He walks to a cliff, throws the goblet into the sea, closes his eyes, and dies. The mood of "The King of Thulé" and the depiction of the king in "Dream-land" are very similar, perhaps reflecting Poe's own losses and reliance on drinking. "Faust" was also adapted into a romantic drama by H P Grattan in 1842, less than a year before Poe used the term "Thule" in "The Pit and the Pendulum."

Poe references Thule twice in his collected works. Once in "The Pit and the Pendulum," where he mentions "ultima Thule," and twice in "Dream-land," as the opening and closing of the poem. "The King of Thulé" and "Dream-land" can be read as companion pieces. In "Dream-land," the speaker describes Thule as dark and lonely, haunted by dead friends, seeing a colorless shadow world. These scenes echo Goethe’s "The King of Thulé," as he has just lost his wife, feels lonely, and has lost the will to rule or even live. The entire poem reads as though the speaker has walked into Goethe's poem.

Goethe was a significant author whom Poe would likely have known, if only due to his respect for Tennyson. Poe commented on this when asked if he admired Tennyson. Besides the connection to Tennyson, Poe would have been exposed to Goethe’s work through the many reproductions that followed the original publication.

Under California law, a customer injured after slipping on an applesauce spill in a grocery store could potentially be awarded punitive damages by showing that the store manager acted with malice, as he was informed twice about the spill but neglected to clean it for thirty minutes because he was having dinner.

A judge is unlikely to quickly dismiss Jennifer Palmer's claim for punitive damages. To justify such damages, the plaintiff must provide evidence that the defendant acted with a willful and conscious disregard for probable harm and that the conduct was despicable. Palmer can argue that Martin should have known the potential harm of not cleaning the spill, as multiple D&D customers had been injured in similar incidents in the months before Palmer's accident; despite this, he failed to address the spill. Palmer's argument that Martin's actions were despicable is less convincing, but still reasonable given that six slip-and-fall incidents occurred in 2009, and Martin did not take proper actions to ensure the safety of his store.

On October 13, 2009, at 5:00 pm, D&D Markets employee Rich Wayne informed his manager, Paul Martin, of an applesauce spill in an aisle. Martin told Wayne he was on a dinner break and "didn't have time to deal with customer complaints." At 5:15 pm, another employee, Mary J. Haddigan, also informed Mr. Martin of the spill, and Martin responded in the same way. At 5:30 pm, the plaintiff, Jennifer Palmer, slipped and fell on the spill, sustaining a serious back injury. Prior to Palmer's accident, five different slip-and-fall incidents had been reported at D&D in 2009. Palmer is now suing D&D for compensatory and punitive damages related to her injury, and we are considering whether to file a motion for partial summary judgment against the punitive damage claim.

In California, a plaintiff can recover punitive damages for a breach of an obligation not arising out of a contract if the defendant acted with "oppression, fraud, or malice." Cal. Civ. Code, § 3294(a) (Lexis 2010). The statute defines malice as conduct intended to cause harm, or in the absence of intent, the conduct must be "despicable" and carried out with "a willful and conscious disregard of the rights or safety of others." Courts have described conduct as malicious when committed with a conscious disregard for the plaintiff's rights, where the defendant "was aware of the probable dangerous consequences of his conduct, and that he willfully and deliberately failed to avoid those consequences." Taylor v. Super. Ct. of Los Angeles Co., 598 P. 2d 853, 856 (Cal. 1979).

She always felt like she needed something, a desire that was never fulfilled. It began at around 14, as she entered her teenage years. By the age of 17, the feeling lingered. She realized she wanted someone rather than something, yet she wasn't interested in any boys. Some tried to woo her awkwardly, but none caught her attention. She often questioned herself about this strange feeling, wondering what could cause such a thing in a teenage girl. Years of contemplation brought theories, but none convincing enough. So she lived, questioning her desires.

A day at home was usually peaceful. Her parents were kind and calm, rarely arguing even with their daughter. The only disputes were about her asserting her independence and free spirit. As the daughter of a serene couple, her vibrant and fun personality made her quite likable.

Today, however, was not calm. As she wandered from room to room seeking inspiration, she heard a scream from the kitchen, her mother's beautiful voice. She rushed in, panicking, "Mom?! Mom, what's wrong?!" Her mother lay on the floor, appearing in pain, repeatedly saying "Ow" with short breaths. The daughter ran to her, offering help. "Ouch... sweetheart, I... need you to take me to the hospital." The words were rushed, and her daughter could see the pain. "Okay Mom, tell me how to get you there." Her mother guided her hands, and the house's hero was grateful for her strength training classes. She carried her mother to the car, laid her in the back, and drove.

At the hospital, the smell of disinfectant and sickness mingled with fear, but she was too focused on her mother to notice. She quickly brought her injured mother in, calling for doctors. Worried faces gathered, and someone brought a rolling bed to lay her mother on. They took her for immediate examination, leaving the daughter to worry.

Her mother had fallen off a stepping stool trying to reach a vase from the highest cabinet.

This study aimed to demonstrate that a high "alternate Mediterranean (aMed) diet score" is associated with a reduced risk of chronic heart disease (CHD), stroke, and stroke mortality. The aMed diet is a modified version of the Mediterranean diet, characterized by higher consumption of plant foods, including plant proteins (excluding potatoes but including fruits, nuts, whole grains, and legumes), monounsaturated fats (compared to saturated fats), and fish, with lower intake of animal products and saturated fats. Moderate alcohol consumption is allowed.

Previous prospective studies documented an inverse relationship between adherence to a Mediterranean diet and the risk of total and cardiovascular disease (CVD) mortality. An intervention trial showed that the Mediterranean diet was more effective than a low-fat diet in promoting weight loss and reducing the total cholesterol to high-density lipoprotein cholesterol ratio in obese individuals. Prior studies did not focus specifically on stroke or stroke mortality.

This epidemiological study followed 74,886 women aged 38 to 63, without a history of CVD or diabetes, who participated in the Nurses' Health Study, a cohort study of 121,700 female nurses across 11 US states. From 1984 to 2004, the authors calculated the aMed diet score six times based on self-reported "food frequency questionnaires" (FFQs) designed to assess nutrient intake over the previous year. More than 95% of nurses continued participation throughout the 20-year period. FFQs were validated. Reports of CHD, fatal CHD, and stroke were confirmed by reviewing medical or hospital records, autopsies, or death certificates. In cases where records were unavailable, cases were considered "probable" and included, with about 17% of strokes and 24% of nonfatal myocardial infarcts classified as such. Body mass index, smoking status, aspirin use, multivitamin intake, menopausal status, and postmenopausal hormone use were calculated for each FFQ, and leisure-time physical activity was assessed starting in 1986.

To reduce random variation for individuals and better represent long-term dietary intake, cumulative averages of the aMed score from repeated FFQs were calculated (averaging scores from the two prior years). Adjustments were made for "confounders" by adjusting for age, smoking, BMI, menopausal status, postmenopausal hormone use, multivitamin intake, alcohol intake, physical activity, and aspirin use.

Cox proportional-hazard modeling was used to assess the association between the aMed score and the risk of CHD and stroke, using separate models for fatal and nonfatal CHD and stroke types.

Greater adherence to the Mediterranean diet, as indicated by a higher aMed diet score, was associated with a lower risk of CHD and stroke in women. During the 20-year follow-up, 2,391 cases of CHD, 1,763 cases of stroke, and 1,077 cardiovascular disease deaths (combining fatal CHD and strokes) were documented. Women in the top aMed quintile had a lower risk for both CHD and stroke compared to those in the bottom quintile (relative risk [RR], 0.71).

Hitler is alive in Burma, says the sign.

Ellen Page, star of Juno, stands alone on a street corner, holding a piece of cardboard above her head with an unsettling message written in Sharpie. Burma, also known as Myanmar, is a Southeastern Asian country ruled by a tyrannical military junta that seized power in a 1962 coup. In 2007, street protests erupted, marking the first public demonstrations in a decade. Led by a large number of Burmese monks, these protests were dubbed "The Saffron Revolution," named after the color of the monks' robes. After the initial uprisings, public interest grew, and though the Burmese government initially allowed monks to gather peacefully, violence soon escalated into what some saw as a full-scale war between the monks and the junta, with the military invading and looting monasteries nationwide. Foreign journalists were rounded up and jailed, with a Japanese photojournalist named Kenji Nagai killed on September 27, 2007, merely for being at a street protest. Although official reports state 13 people were killed, Colonel Hla Win, who defected from the army days before the official report, claimed, "Far more people have been killed in recent days than you've heard. The bodies number in the thousands."

This is nothing new. While these are some of the most recent examples of atrocities in our world, the desire of governments to silence dissent and maintain total control over their citizens has existed since the dawn of civilization. Early Roman emperors declared themselves chosen by the gods to have complete executive authority over every aspect of their society. Japanese emperors were believed to be gods, sent to our world to lead their people to prosperity through inventions like Motorola cell phones and hara-kiri. Meanwhile, our current president, George W. Bush, holds weekly conference calls with Ted Haggard, leader of Stupid People Worldwide, a subsidiary of the Republican Party.

Some well-known examples of such actions include the June 4, 1989, protest in Tiananmen Square, where intellectuals, labor activists, and students gathered to protest the government's authoritarian rule. The death toll in that incident varies widely, with official Chinese reports stating 200-300 dead, while the Chinese Red Cross reported 2,000-3,000 deaths. Another is the Rwandan genocide of the 1990s, where Hutu militia groups, aided by the Rwandan government, systematically killed all Tutsis and political moderates, regardless of ethnic background. Hitler's 'Third Reich,' a period spanning several years and countries where anyone of Jewish descent was rounded up and killed, is another extreme example.

Duke Ellington's legacy in jazz is largely due to his longevity and his creative ability to shape his orchestra. In many of the compositions selected for this assignment, Ellington's presence on the piano is subtle, but as a composer, he excelled at creating rich and complex pieces that showcased the individual talents of band members. Ellington crafted a framework that allowed soloists to freely improvise, in addition to writing tightly orchestrated pieces that utilized the unique styles of band members to highlight musical ideas. In doing so, he emphasized the overall tone of the orchestra, creating coherent and original sounds to suit each piece. His mastery of the individual players' sounds and how they fit together in an evolving ensemble enabled him to write some of the most innovative and brilliant pieces in jazz history. The Grove Music Dictionary, when discussing Ellington's sound and innovation, mentions "Creole Love Call," referring to his use of voice "as a jazz instrument" throughout his career. This is an early example of Ellington's use of voice to add texture and color without the constraints of lyrics. "Creole Love Call" also demonstrates Ellington's ability to complement the style of his soloists, something evident throughout his career. This slow, deliberate twelve-bar blues piece contains six choruses, as follows: Chorus 1: Call and response between voice and reeds, where the voice starts smooth and melodic, then transitions to a rougher sound at the end. Chorus 2: Muted trumpet solo that elaborates on the basic melody and emphasizes several extended blue notes. Chorus 3: Sweeping clarinet solo in a high register, backed by a subtle syncopated piano phrase. Chorus 4: Full band echoes the first chorus with a call and response by the brass and reed sections. Chorus 5: The climactic chorus of the piece, as the reeds now begin the call and response in a high register, backed by syncopated stop time from the brass and rhythm sections. Chorus 6: A return to the structure of the first chorus, with call and response between voice and reeds. In this chorus, the voice employs the "growl" technique, soloing as an instrument. Tag: A brief tag featuring a vocal run and a dissonant novelty ending by a trombone. Ellington's use of voice to add a dimension of tone color is an example of a stylistic trait that permeates his work. In "Hot and Bothered," recorded a year later, Ellington combines his skill at tight orchestration with his ear for tone color. A call and response phrase between "Bubber" Miley on muted trumpet and Baby Cox's scat singing uses the vocal elements of Miley's playing and the instrumental aspects of Cox's voice to create a rich and complementary sound. "It Don’t Mean a Thing (If It Ain’t Got That Swing)" extends these ideas, as Ellington uses Joe "Tricky Sam" Nanton, a mainstay in Ellington's orchestra, to great effect in introducing the melody on muted trombone.

Why do organisms evolve in the way they do? Are there limitations or constraints that affect the direction of evolutionary change? Although D’Arcy Thompson stated in 1917 that "Even now, the zoologist has scarcely begun to dream of defining even the simplest organic forms in mathematical language," this is still true today. Recently, mathematical modeling has been applied to general aspects of mollusk skeletogenesis through both ontogeny and phylogeny (e.g., Raup and Stanley, 1981). Our study is exploring how mathematical modeling of ontogenetic and phylogenetic changes in Prunum, in conjunction with experimental studies, can be used to elucidate the mechanisms involved in the direction and magnitude of evolutionary-developmental change. We used X-ray images of Prunum species to delineate quantitative parameters, which could then be used to model hypothetical and actual skeletal morphologies. These parameters were entered into the software program CerioShell (Stone, 1995). We modeled hypothetical shell morphologies that could interpret the boundaries of possible morphological change in Prunum. These results are combined with experimental and descriptive studies to better understand macroevolutionary events in this clade.

A shell can be thought of as a tubular structure that travels through time in 360 degrees of space. These revolutions or turns of a coiled shell are called whorls, which are considered to spiral around an imaginary central axis. This axis runs through the central column of the shell and is known as the columella. The rate at which the whorls enlarge can vary, and a continuous line separates each whorl, referred to as a suture. In most shells, the largest whorl of a shell is the last whorl (body whorl). The spire is considered to be all the whorls except the last. The apex is the tip of the spire, and the opposite end is referred to as the base. The animal extends out of its shell through an opening called the aperture.

Shells can be viewed in apical, basal, apertural, and abapertural views. (The "usual" orientation of a shell is an apertural view, with the aperture facing the viewer and the apex pointing up.)

A method for counting whorls is shown below. First, the shell should be viewed from the apical view and then it should be determined where the first suture begins. A line can then be drawn dividing the shell into two parts. Whorls are counted from this line and estimated to a quarter of a whorl.

A shell can be viewed as a series of apertures that travel through time and space as the animal builds its shell. It is possible to trace the path of the aperture via coordinates of the center of each whorl’s aperture as well as the horizontal and vertical radius of the aperture.

This trajectory can be graphically and mathematically represented. Once a mathematical formulation is made, it is then possible to vary parameters and modify the mollusk’s skeletogenesis.

Over the past decade, the neonatal and infant mortality rates in Indonesia have remained relatively stable. While the country has made progress on the Millennium Development Goals, particularly in water and sanitation, the improvements in child and maternal health are far from the levels needed to meet the 2015 targets. Various reasons for these shortcomings will be discussed below, highlighting the need to strengthen the healthcare system rather than just focus on programmatic interventions.

Indonesia has seen improvements in the number of births attended by skilled health workers, with 72% of deliveries meeting this standard. However, this category still includes traditional workers like midwives who cannot provide medical interventions when complications arise (hence the high percentage of maternal deaths due to hemorrhage). This means the improvements in this indicator can be misleading, and there's still much work to be done. Additionally, there has been a decline in the percentage of children under five with diarrhea being treated by health professionals. Although postnatal care data is incomplete, it is clear that this area is also a concern, with low rates nationwide.

Cesarean section rates remain lower than expected, around 4%. The c-section rates further highlight another concerning issue. While the rate is 7% in urban areas, it drops to only 2% in rural areas, pointing to the equity of coverage problem across the country. Clearly, access to healthcare services is concentrated in urban regions. Another access issue involves vertical equity, with a 27% gap in service utilization between the poorest and richest quintiles. Clearly, the poor find it much more difficult to access healthcare services, likely due to out-of-pocket costs.

When discussing next steps to improve neonatal and maternal care indicators, the most fundamental question is how to most effectively address the lack of services. Specifically, should Indonesia develop program-specific approaches, or should it strengthen the overall health system without focusing solely on pre- and post-pregnancy care for mothers and children? There is no doubt that programmatic approaches to solve the problems outlined above are appealing. "Vertical approaches" not only have more targeted and manageable objectives for specific improvement sectors but also generally yield faster results. However, some drawbacks must be considered. One major drawback is that heavy investment in one particular health sector often means other areas suffer from reduced funding, and human resources are drawn to the more resource-rich areas (the effect of international funding on HIV/AIDS and its impact on the family planning sector is one example). Furthermore, running multiple parallel programs in one area can lead to duplication of services and lack of coordination between programs, increasing forms and paperwork for supplies and funding.

The classification of popular music has expanded over the past 100 years to encompass so many genres that listing them all definitively is challenging. Adding to the complexity, most, if not all, genres—such as rap, rock, country, jazz, and folk—have developed multiple sub-genres and sub-sub-genres within their realms. Arguably, the sub-genre of Heavy Metal rock has become one of the most diverse and expressive genres of all popular music in the past 40 years. It is expressive because it showcases a wide range of emotions, though they tend to lean toward the darker side of the spectrum. It is diverse because soon after the genre's inception, people realized its flexibility and began to create their own sub-genres, followed by sub-sub-genres, continuing the evolution to this day.

Today, we have reached a point in the heavy metal movement where there are so many niche groups that it is hard to define exactly what heavy metal is. It has grown to incorporate many themes from other genres, but like everything else, it originated from somewhere. To properly understand the metal music that exists everywhere today, one must first understand what the metal movement is and why it is considered a movement rather than just a genre.

In many ways, metal is a movement defined by darkness. Metal can be seen as a "music of more"—more bass, more volume, more violence, more theatricality. Less primitivism, more skill; people in metal bands really know how to play their instruments, and it shows in the music. Metal is also, unsurprisingly, a movement heavily influenced by drugs. There was a psychedelic drug boom in the mid-70s that led to people getting wilder, prompting them to make crazy, otherworldly records, using drugs as a scapegoat for their creativity. It possesses many dark, visceral qualities, which were new to the music scene because much popular music did not reflect the darker side of the emotional spectrum. Additionally, later generations of metal have drawn some of their influence from the dark, visceral qualities prominent in the Romantic Era. Lyrics like the following express the darkness that is a hallmark of the movement: (Byrne)

These lyrics from Helter Skelter display the darker side of the Beatles. It exhibits ups and downs, supposedly influenced by drugs. This song is considered by some to be one of the first Heavy Metal songs. It was a response to a Rolling Stones song that was also heavy and dark. The Beatles wanted to prove they could be as heavy as the Stones, so they included it on The White Album.

A few decades before Surrealists began crafting their dreamlike works, Henri Rousseau was meticulously creating his own dreams, both literally and metaphorically. The Dream, a 1910 painting by the renowned Post-Impressionist artist, not only depicts a woman marveling at the wonders of a land she visits in a dream but also embodies Rousseau's personal dreams and ambitions as a painter. From the outset of his career, he aspired for recognition, acceptance, and acclaim from other artists and art enthusiasts and faced an internal struggle to achieve this aspiration. The Dream best illustrates Rousseau's lifelong internal conflict: to conform or imitate certain painting styles to gain acceptance in the critical art world he cherished, or to maintain creative independence and uniqueness, forging his own path.

Before analyzing The Dream from this perspective, one must be acquainted with Rousseau’s life story. Henri Rousseau was born on May 21, 1844, in Laval, a town in northwest France. His father was a tinsmith and hardware dealer who "enjoyed bourgeois prosperity" (Shattuck 47). Without formal artistic training, Rousseau worked until the age of forty as a gabelou, an employee of the municipal toll service, although he was mistakenly nicknamed douanier, a customs inspector (Shattuck 46). The death of his first wife, Clémence, following the deaths of eight infant children, left Rousseau with only one child, a daughter named Julia, and profound grief (Shattuck 49). Consequently, he sought refuge in a new life, turning to painting for solace and new beginnings. Unlike his contemporaries who sentimentalized and romanticized peasants in art, Rousseau was essentially a folk painter, sharing the hopes and dreams of the average member of his class.

Rousseau's obsession with being accepted by the art world is understandable in context: as discussed, he lacked formal art education and began his career later in life, producing work alongside many other talented and more renowned modern artists. Despite years of work, Rousseau only began to receive proper recognition for his art around the same time Matisse started to establish himself as an artist. In the book Modern French Painters, author Jan Gordon asserts that while technically competitors in the art field, they differed not only in style and subject but also in their fundamental reasons for painting: "Matisse was a painter who feared painting in a clichéd manner, while Rousseau desired to create a painting so conventional that he would be accepted into the Artiste Français" (92).

Many great thinkers have suggested a deep connection between ethics and aesthetics, between truth and beauty. I believe there is a fundamental reason for this. As John Keats states in "Ode on a Grecian Urn," "Beauty is truth, truth beauty — that is all / Ye know on earth, and all ye need to know."
