Indonesia has seen improvements in the number of births attended by skilled health workers, with 72% of deliveries meeting this standard. However, this category still includes traditional workers like midwives who cannot provide medical interventions when complications arise (hence the high percentage of maternal deaths due to hemorrhage). This means the improvements in this indicator can be misleading, and there's still much work to be done. Additionally, there has been a decline in the percentage of children under five with diarrhea being treated by health professionals. Although postnatal care data is incomplete, it is clear that this area is also a concern, with low rates nationwide.

Cesarean section rates remain lower than expected, around 4%. The c-section rates further highlight another concerning issue. While the rate is 7% in urban areas, it drops to only 2% in rural areas, pointing to the equity of coverage problem across the country. Clearly, access to healthcare services is concentrated in urban regions. Another access issue involves vertical equity, with a 27% gap in service utilization between the poorest and richest quintiles. Clearly, the poor find it much more difficult to access healthcare services, likely due to out-of-pocket costs.

When discussing next steps to improve neonatal and maternal care indicators, the most fundamental question is how to most effectively address the lack of services. Specifically, should Indonesia develop program-specific approaches, or should it strengthen the overall health system without focusing solely on pre- and post-pregnancy care for mothers and children? There is no doubt that programmatic approaches to solve the problems outlined above are appealing. "Vertical approaches" not only have more targeted and manageable objectives for specific improvement sectors but also generally yield faster results. However, some drawbacks must be considered. One major drawback is that heavy investment in one particular health sector often means other areas suffer from reduced funding, and human resources are drawn to the more resource-rich areas (the effect of international funding on HIV/AIDS and its impact on the family planning sector is one example). Furthermore, running multiple parallel programs in one area can lead to duplication of services and lack of coordination between programs, increasing forms and paperwork for supplies and funding.

The classification of popular music has expanded over the past 100 years to encompass so many genres that listing them all definitively is challenging. Adding to the complexity, most, if not all, genres—such as rap, rock, country, jazz, and folk—have developed multiple sub-genres and sub-sub-genres within their realms. Arguably, the sub-genre of Heavy Metal rock has become one of the most diverse and expressive genres of all popular music in the past 40 years. It is expressive because it showcases a wide range of emotions, though they tend to lean toward the darker side of the spectrum. It is diverse because soon after the genre's inception, people realized its flexibility and began to create their own sub-genres, followed by sub-sub-genres, continuing the evolution to this day.

Today, we have reached a point in the heavy metal movement where there are so many niche groups that it is hard to define exactly what heavy metal is. It has grown to incorporate many themes from other genres, but like everything else, it originated from somewhere. To properly understand the metal music that exists everywhere today, one must first understand what the metal movement is and why it is considered a movement rather than just a genre.

In many ways, metal is a movement defined by darkness. Metal can be seen as a "music of more"—more bass, more volume, more violence, more theatricality. Less primitivism, more skill; people in metal bands really know how to play their instruments, and it shows in the music. Metal is also, unsurprisingly, a movement heavily influenced by drugs. There was a psychedelic drug boom in the mid-70s that led to people getting wilder, prompting them to make crazy, otherworldly records, using drugs as a scapegoat for their creativity. It possesses many dark, visceral qualities, which were new to the music scene because much popular music did not reflect the darker side of the emotional spectrum. Additionally, later generations of metal have drawn some of their influence from the dark, visceral qualities prominent in the Romantic Era. Lyrics like the following express the darkness that is a hallmark of the movement: (Byrne)

These lyrics from Helter Skelter display the darker side of the Beatles. It exhibits ups and downs, supposedly influenced by drugs. This song is considered by some to be one of the first Heavy Metal songs. It was a response to a Rolling Stones song that was also heavy and dark. The Beatles wanted to prove they could be as heavy as the Stones, so they included it on The White Album.

A few decades before Surrealists began crafting their dreamlike works, Henri Rousseau was meticulously creating his own dreams, both literally and metaphorically. The Dream, a 1910 painting by the renowned Post-Impressionist artist, not only depicts a woman marveling at the wonders of a land she visits in a dream but also embodies Rousseau's personal dreams and ambitions as a painter. From the outset of his career, he aspired for recognition, acceptance, and acclaim from other artists and art enthusiasts and faced an internal struggle to achieve this aspiration. The Dream best illustrates Rousseau's lifelong internal conflict: to conform or imitate certain painting styles to gain acceptance in the critical art world he cherished, or to maintain creative independence and uniqueness, forging his own path.

Before analyzing The Dream from this perspective, one must be acquainted with Rousseau’s life story. Henri Rousseau was born on May 21, 1844, in Laval, a town in northwest France. His father was a tinsmith and hardware dealer who "enjoyed bourgeois prosperity" (Shattuck 47). Without formal artistic training, Rousseau worked until the age of forty as a gabelou, an employee of the municipal toll service, although he was mistakenly nicknamed douanier, a customs inspector (Shattuck 46). The death of his first wife, Clémence, following the deaths of eight infant children, left Rousseau with only one child, a daughter named Julia, and profound grief (Shattuck 49). Consequently, he sought refuge in a new life, turning to painting for solace and new beginnings. Unlike his contemporaries who sentimentalized and romanticized peasants in art, Rousseau was essentially a folk painter, sharing the hopes and dreams of the average member of his class.

Rousseau's obsession with being accepted by the art world is understandable in context: as discussed, he lacked formal art education and began his career later in life, producing work alongside many other talented and more renowned modern artists. Despite years of work, Rousseau only began to receive proper recognition for his art around the same time Matisse started to establish himself as an artist. In the book Modern French Painters, author Jan Gordon asserts that while technically competitors in the art field, they differed not only in style and subject but also in their fundamental reasons for painting: "Matisse was a painter who feared painting in a clichéd manner, while Rousseau desired to create a painting so conventional that he would be accepted into the Artiste Français" (92).

Many great thinkers have suggested a deep connection between ethics and aesthetics, between truth and beauty. I believe there is a fundamental reason for this. As John Keats states in "Ode on a Grecian Urn," "Beauty is truth, truth beauty — that is all / Ye know on earth, and all ye need to know." Much of what we learn in life comes through education or experience. However, as Keats implies, we seem to appreciate ethics and aesthetics without being explicitly taught. Both ethics and aesthetics are attempts to describe rather than prescribe. Our studies of morality and beauty largely aim to explain why a piece of art or literature is beautiful, or why an action is moral, rather than establishing rules for judging or creating good art or moral behavior.

Furthermore, criticism of art or morals can never fully capture the essence of what is good or beautiful. For example, discussions about the value of da Vinci's Mona Lisa may focus on elements like foreground, background, contrast, or cultural context, but ultimately, these do not explain why it is great art. Instead, when asked about a favorite work of art or literature, it is common to hear a phrase like "there's just something special about it" before a more detailed explanation follows. I believe that both art and morals cannot be completely reduced to descriptions of their qualities. As Flannery O'Connor says, "A story is a way to say something that can't be said any other way... you tell a story because a statement would be inadequate." No matter how thoroughly we describe the characteristics of a literary work, there is something transcendent that remains. I believe ethics shares this quality. As Wittgenstein points out, "It is clear that ethics cannot be expressed. / Ethics is transcendental." I suggest that this "something," this ineffable quality, is the most powerful attribute of art and morality, and that this transcendental nature of both ethics and aesthetics provides a link between them.

I believe morality and art are closely related because we experience both at a noumenal level, to use a Kantian term. They affect us in a way that can be felt but not fully explained. This link is even more pronounced in the art of literature. As McKean says, "What most distinguishes literature from the other arts, what is, in truth, unique about the art, is its moral quality. Moral standards may be inappropriate for other arts, like music, but they seem as relevant to literature as they are to life itself. Living necessarily involves values... Literature is important to us precisely because of the values we find there."

Today's Germany is seen as a powerful and united nation, with a unique culture stretching from the shadows of the Alps in Munich to the Baltic city of Kiel. This culture is felt from Cologne on the Rhine, through central Germany to the Saxon city of Dresden on the Elbe. It's no surprise that the Germany we know today has roots in various different sources and tribes.

Germania is the ancestral land of the Germans, with the origins of its name being highly debated among scholars and historians. Tacitus claimed the name came from a Germanic tribe known as the Tungrians, who were previously called Germans before they crossed the Rhine and fought the Gauls (Tacitus, 98). Julius Caesar first used the term “Germanus” in his commentaries on the Gallic Wars, where he subdued the Gauls and battled with Germanic tribes that often crossed the Rhine with mischievous intentions. He borrowed this term from the Gauls to differentiate those he conquered (the Gauls) from those he did not. While the origin is uncertain, some believe it referred to a neighbor in the Gaulish language. In the first chapter of his first book on these wars, Julius Caesar notes: “Germans, who live beyond the Rhine, with whom the Gauls are continually waging war... They engage in almost daily battles with the Germans.” (Julius Caesar, 50-40 BC) Others suggest the meaning comes from the spear used in warfare, called a ger (O.E.D, 2010), or perhaps from the Old Irish word garim, meaning “to shout,” indicating that the Germans were loud or boisterous. (Names of Germany)

The early Roman historian Tacitus, in his AD 98 work “De Origine et situ Germanorum,” which recounts the origins of the Germans, wrote: “I should regard the Germans as aboriginal, not at all mixed with other races through immigration or intercourse. For, in former times it was not by land but by ship that those who sought to emigrate would arrive... Who would leave Asia or Africa for Italy to reach Germany, with its wild lands, harsh skies, and gloomy customs and appearance, unless indeed it was his home?” (Tacitus, 98)

And who would leave Rome for Germania? Certainly not the Romans, at least not yet. They would send their conquests into the lands of Germania for goods and occasionally launch land campaigns, but in the end, they mostly returned to their sprawling empire. As the Germanic tribes began to appear in the middle of the first century, they lived on the borders of the Roman Empire, trading goods taken from the land and serving within the Roman army to demonstrate their skills. (Ozment, 2005 pg. 17)

The play Twelfth Night suggests that while disguise can be helpful in sustaining long-term deception, ultimately, a person must abandon this newly formed identity to avoid losing themselves. However, the challenge of ending deception is that it may lead to alienation. Thus, one faces a choice between self-preservation and maintaining relationships with others. Some may react neutrally to discovering they've been deceived, but others may be offended by the charade. Deception in gender role reversal is particularly complex, raising questions such as why someone feels the need to abandon their identity and take on the guise of the opposite gender. In Viola's case, it is a form of self-protection: "I'll bring you to a captain in this town/Where lie my maiden weeds, by whose gentle help/I was preserved to serve this noble count..." (5.1.247-249). Upon arriving in a foreign land, Viola feels compelled to pretend to be a man to protect herself from potential threats. Her plan succeeds but isolates her from the women around her, severing an important support system. Worse, she is so convincing as a man that Olivia confuses her with Sebastian and falls in love with her. "Whither, my lord? Cesario, husband, stay." (5.1.138). Additionally, she must contend with suppressed romantic feelings between her and Orsino: "Boy, thou hast said to me a thousand times/Thou never shouldst love woman like to me." (5.1.260-261). Although this may seem progressive, modern readers might view Twelfth Night as illustrating how deception can reveal hidden emotions, particularly in Olivia and Orsino's cases. Certain passages suggest these characters have unexpressed desires that Viola/Cesario's appearance compels them to confront. Is Olivia attracted to Cesario because he seems male, or does she secretly have feelings for women? This is unlikely, as Shakespeare's Olivia seems to parody those who judge others solely by appearance. This is shown by how easily Olivia transfers her affections from Cesario to Sebastian and begins to see Cesario/Viola as family rather than a romantic interest: "A sister, you are she." (5.1.315).

German colonial rule is noted for its brutality by many observers, particularly regarding the genocide of the Ovaherero and Nama in German South West Africa. Naturally, an entire colonial empire cannot be described with such simplicity. The German colonial empire was diverse in both policy and governing style, as well as geography. Educational provisions across the colonies were similarly varied. When the British took over German East Africa (Tanganyika) in 1919, they found a large number of educated and literate Africans. German educational efforts in Cameroon and other colonies were praised by contemporary authors. 

In contrast, the situation in South West Africa (present-day Namibia) was markedly different. Unlike East Africa, where the government established state schools and played a key role in native education, in South West Africa, the task was almost entirely left to missionary societies with limited government support. However, the government did invest significant resources in educating Europeans in the colony, establishing state schools and providing more support and regulation for missionary schools. These educational policies had long-lasting effects in South West Africa even after German rule ended. While other German colonies had significant numbers of literate and educated Africans, in South West Africa, "the overwhelming majority of the population remained untouched, uneducated, and illiterate." Various social, political, and economic factors led to the different experiences in South West Africa. This paper seeks to expand the discussion by identifying these factors and focusing on new research regarding settler and colonial authorities' attitudes towards native Africans.

There is extensive literature specifically addressing education in the German colonial empire. Most of these sources are in German and were written in the early twentieth century, during or shortly after the period of German colonial rule. The primary aim of early works was to describe the features of educational systems in these colonies. Later English writings expanded the discourse through comparative studies of education in various German colonies and more detailed analyses of specific aspects of education. These studies highlighted significant differences in the educational systems of different colonies. The most prominent work addressing the topic of this paper is Cohen's study of education in South West Africa and East Africa. Cohen compares the educational systems of the two colonies and discusses the factors accounting for their differences. According to Cohen, the large settler population in South West Africa explains many of the unique aspects of the colony's educational system.

Compared to Germany's other colonial possessions, South West Africa had a relatively temperate climate, although much of the territory was covered by arid desert. The European population in South West Africa reflected these relatively hospitable conditions. By 1913, nearly 15,000 whites lived in South West Africa, while only 5,336 lived in the colony with the next largest settler population, East Africa.

The United States and Mexico are examples of two nations that once experienced a prolonged rivalry lasting 57 years, from 1836 to 1893 (Diehl and Goerts 2000, p. 145). The peak of this rivalry was the Mexican-American War of 1846-1848, during which the United States attacked and defeated Mexico, acquiring Texas and the American Southwest as new territories. Numerous other conflicts occurred between the two nations, finally subsiding just before World War I. The rivalry began as Americans and Mexicans clashed over key issues such as religion, culture, and tradition, and had significant material interest conflicts (Schmitt 1974, p. 30-31).

This situation is not unlike the enduring rivalries many other countries have with their neighbors. Nations sharing borders often experience clashes of interests that lead to the formation of competitive stances between them. The United States and Mexico are similar to many other enduring rivalries between countries that share a common border. David M. Pletcher (1977) states that "only in Mexico and Cuba can one find long-lasting overarching American diplomatic problems" (p. 41). Indeed, both these nations are geographically close to the United States and have been rivals, whereas other countries in Latin America have enjoyed and continue to enjoy good relations with the United States.

Religious issues created a rift between the two countries, a problem that has troubled many nations throughout history. Sally Frahm (2001) states that "if in the twentieth century Americans opposed fascism and communism, in the eighteenth and nineteenth centuries they opposed Catholicism and monarchy" (p. 86). This is somewhat similar to the Cold War rivalry between the United States and the Soviet Union, which was partly an ideological struggle and partly a competition over interests deemed vital by each nation. In this case, however, the ideological struggle was not based on political structures but rather on the religious preferences of the United States and Mexico. This distrust originated from the distrust between the English and the Spanish. Inheriting these feelings of distrust from their former colonial rulers was a major obstacle in establishing amicable foreign relations between the United States and Mexico.

Diehl and Goerts (2000) list 17 disputes between Mexico and the United States during the 57-year rivalry period. Most disputes described by Diehl and Goerts during this period involved territorial issues related to border raids from Mexican territory into the U.S. and other frontier problems. Border raids by bandits and outlaws from American border towns were a major issue that persisted until both the United States and Mexico exerted military force on their borders (Schmitt 1974, p. 97).

Schmitt (1974) explains that the rivalry between the two nations began to subside as "Mexico became clearly dependent on the United States in a substantial way" (p. 109) and eventually ended as American ambitions "changed from territorial expansion to economic intervention into Mexico" (p. 110) in the later part of the 19th century.

Fifteen years ago, I suddenly and unexpectedly became disabled due to an illness I had never heard of.

At that time, I was a nurse. I chose this profession because I lacked safety and security during my childhood. "You'll always be able to find work; people will always get sick." This was the mantra I heard repeatedly in my adolescence and beyond. So, even though my dream was to be a scientist or journalist—preferably a bit of both—I chose nursing.

However, there I was at 46, single, with almost no money in the bank and unable to work. To this day, I am still disabled, and after living on Social Security Disability for 15 years, I have almost nothing left that I can call "mine." I manage to get by, but every day is a challenge to my sense of security, safety, and self-esteem. Nothing in my life is certain anymore, yet there is one thing I know for sure. I couldn't have made it through these years without the help of my family and a few good friends, no matter how strong I was. Believe me, when real disaster strikes, you feel very helpless.

My point is that there will always be emergencies in life, both big and small. There are no guarantees, and no matter how well-prepared you are, some things are just too overwhelming to handle alone.

I completely agree that we in the U.S. need to stop relying entirely on big government; it's decaying and falling apart, anyway. However, I would much rather see Americans learn to trust each other again—learning to help each other and to ask for help—instead of everyone individually building fallout shelters in their backyards.

The Conservatives in the U.S. talk about the "rugged individualism" that built this country, but in truth, what sustained our forefathers during hard times wasn't rugged individualism; it was compassion, mutual respect, and the sharing of resources. The pioneers who crossed the Rockies in wagon trains didn't reach the coast by going it alone.

So, by all means, be prepared. I am. I have a disaster kit, first aid supplies, water purification tablets, plastic sheeting, and duct tape for the windows in case of a biological attack. I have several flashlights, all sorts of batteries, lots and lots of candles, waterproof matches, and canned goods, too. If you have the land and resources to establish a small farm and can preserve your own food, do it. It's a great idea, as is a wood stove, as long as you don't live in an apartment.

But while you're at it, get to know your neighbors.

Some time during the fifth or sixth century BCE, a prince was born who would later be known as Buddha. Throughout his life, he renounced worldly life and attained enlightenment, and his teachings led to the establishment of Buddhism, with its most orthodox sect known as Theravada Buddhism. This religion has been around for approximately 2,500 years, and it appears different today than it did during Buddha's time. This change can be observed globally, for example, in the Theravada country of Sri Lanka, where the annual water-cutting ceremony takes place. Both monks and laypeople participate in this ceremony, which holds religious significance despite Buddha not having taught such festivities. These differences range from superficial traditions to the core of the religion's soteriology. The Theravada Buddhist community, from both monastic and lay perspectives, has had to adapt its doctrinal principles over time. This is due to both internal and external forces, as well as hostile and benign influences.

In this discussion, several terms will be frequently used. There is the concept of internal versus external forces. Here, an internal force is defined as one originating from members of the Buddhist community, regardless of monastic status. An external force is any influence from non-Buddhists. A hostile force is any influence that harms or intends to harm the Buddhist community, stemming from a negative view of Buddhism. A benign force is one that neither intends to harm nor help the Buddhist community, though it might inadvertently do one or the other. These terms will recur throughout this discussion.

Firstly, it is essential to examine the basics of the religion—the doctrines at the heart of Theravada Buddhism. Buddhists seek refuge in the triple gem: the Buddha, the Dhamma, and the Sangha. The Dhamma is primarily composed of the Tripitaka—the three baskets—of Buddhist texts. The Sutta Pitaka contains all the Suttas, the Vinaya Pitaka contains the disciplinary rules, and the Abhidhamma Pitaka contains the metaphysical aspects of Buddhism. These metaphysical concepts include Anatta—no soul, Dukkha—life's inherent suffering, and Anicca—the impermanence of everything. Only by understanding these concepts can one end Samsara, the continuous cycle of death and rebirth. Along with the end of Samsara, lobha—desire, dosa—hatred, and moha—delusion will also end when one becomes enlightened. The Vinaya Pitaka sets forth rules for life. For laypeople, there are five precepts (I shall not kill, I shall not lie, I shall not steal, I shall not engage in sexual misconduct, and I shall not consume intoxicating substances). For monks, there are many more disciplinary rules to follow. The most fundamental doctrinal concept in Buddhism is the notion of the Four Noble Truths. First, Dukkha; the truth that life is suffering. Second, attachment causes suffering. Third, suffering can be overcome.
